    market_context: 'Credit cycles in Indian banking follow a predictable pattern: (1) benign period — low NPAs, aggressive lending, loosened underwriting (2) stress emergence — SMA accounts rise, restructuring increases (3) NPA peak — slippages spike, provisioning compresses earnings (4) recovery — write-backs boost earnings, stocks re-rate.\n\nThe key leading indicator is SMA-1 + SMA-2 (Special Mention Accounts) — loans 31-90 days past due. This is the "early warning" that appears 6-12 months before GNPA rises. The vulnerable banks show SMA-1+2 of 3.4-5.2% vs 1.2-1.8% for clean banks. This divergence has historically preceded GNPA inflection by 3-4 quarters.',
    task: '1. Build a credit cycle framework for Indian banks. Where are we in the cycle? Use SMA-1+2 data, restructured book size, and unsecured loan mix as leading indicators.\n\n2. The SMA-1+2 data shows a clear divergence: vulnerable banks at 3.4-5.2% vs clean banks at 1.2-1.8%. If 40-50% of SMA accounts slip to NPA (historical conversion rate), what will GNPA look like in 4 quarters? Model the earnings impact.\n\n3. The vulnerable banks trade at 0.8-1.2x book value. Is this already pricing in the credit cycle turn? Calculate the implied NPA and credit cost assumptions in the current valuations. Are the stocks cheap or still expensive for what\'s coming?\n\n4. Design a long-short banking portfolio: long the 3 cleanest banks, short the 3 most vulnerable. Calculate the expected return spread over 12 months under your credit cycle thesis.',
