    market_context: 'In EPC companies, working capital quality is as important as earnings quality. Key items to watch: (1) Unbilled revenue — work completed but not yet billed to the client. Rising unbilled revenue can mean the company is recognising revenue before the client has certified the work. (2) Retention money — amounts withheld by clients until project completion. (3) Vendor financing — the company is "financing" subcontractors through its own balance sheet.\n\nSterling\'s unbilled revenue has grown from 5.1% to 10.5% of revenue — meaning an increasing proportion of "revenue" hasn\'t been billed to or acknowledged by the client. This is the single most dangerous line item in an EPC company\'s balance sheet.',
